If u r going to shorten "e" in email, the y would u include part of the  symbol represent whatever an electronic mail is. The famous Wilhelm Scream often heard in movies and other audio/visual media got its name from Ben Burt, the sound designer on Spielberg and George Lucas like Star Wars, Indiana Jones, ET, etc. But the first Wilhelm scream was from a man being eaten by an alligator in Distant Drums (1951). The film where the scream got its name from The Charge at Feather River a ‘53 Weatern, where Private Wilhelm was sitting on his horse filling his pipe when an arrow was shot into his leg, causing him to fall off his horse and triggering the famous scream we know and love today. Speaking of fries, you might get a finer v-sauce : french fries are probably not more Belgian than French (full discloser : I am Belgian.)

In french language, french fries are named "frites" (means 'fries', pronounce 'freet'), and started as plain round slices.

French people, since at least the sixties, have tons of (dumb) depreciative jokes about Belgian being stupid and eating frites, because it is a popular meal and we have those iconic, visible, popular, "fritkots" : barracks selling fries along roads.
This makes frites one of the rare inventions from Belgium that French don't claim to be theirs...

As from : https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frite#Origine :
- About the origins of the foodie : "L'origine de la frite serait parisienne, issue de la pratique des marchands ambulants du xviiie siècle qui trimballaient une bassine de friture dans laquelle ils trempaient de la viande et des légumes enduits de pâte à beignet."
- About the English name : "La première attestation de l'expression 'french fries' en anglais est datée de 1894 dans le livre intitulé Rolling Stones de l'écrivain américain O. Henry, précédée en 1884 de French Fried Potatoes. Mais c'est seulement à la fin de la Première Guerre mondiale que cette expression décolla aux États-Unis, lorsque les soldats américains qui avaient goûté des frites dans le nord de la France ou en Belgique sont retournés dans leur pays. Comme la langue parlée dans ces régions était le français, ils les auraient tout simplement appelées French fries."

I find the misnomers about the bird we eat at thanksgiving, and call a turkey, to be one of the weirdest. Several other languages don't attribute their origin to Turkey, so they refer to it as bird of India, Calicut, French, Roman, Ethiopian, Dutch and Greek, depending on the language. None of languages were originally referring to the birds we know in North America, the turkeys everyone else in the Old World is talking about are what we call Guinea fowls. So English attributes the bird originally called turkeys to Guinea instead, and the birds we call turkeys are from America. I think it has something to do with trade lines in the Old World, so each country call the bird after the people they got them from, so like the Malay refer to them as Dutch, the French refer to them as Indian, the Khmer refer to them as French, and all of these are used interchangeably - for instance the French word for the bird we eat at thanksgiving is still d'inde (of India) - despite the bird not coming from India. The Croatians and Hawaiians are closer to correct, they refer to the New World turkeys as Peruvian. New World turkeys weren't Incan though, they actually come from the Mayans. So not Peru. But close. The guinea fowl, the other bird involved, come from India. The reason the two are mixed up to begin with is sort of like why Indigenous Americans are called "Indians". The New World turkeys were similar to the guinea fowls when cooked, so they just started using the same name. It's just so confusing for no reason.

I just thought of something. At what point is a living organism “living”? After all, humans, for example, are in reality a collection of organs and tubular pathways encased by a layer of skin and flesh. We acknowledge that humans are living sentient beings, but when does it stop? Our heart isn’t living because it’s just a collection of tissue with one specific purpose. Our skin is just cells connected tightly together that can stretch. Our lungs are a pair of sacs that convert the air we breathe to supply the rest of our body parts with oxygen. At what point do we become a living being rather than a collection of non-living cells that physically interact with the world through the reactions between other non-living cells?

In other words, when does the non-living become the living?

BTW "hamburger" isn't a minsnomer? It's a wrong way - you say about folk etymology, i.e. people make up totally wrong one  - for tracing misnomers, we always look at the real etymology, not fakes. It would be like telling that "Chicago" is a misnomer, because it has "chi", but it's not a Buddhist thing or even that "Hamburg" is a misnomer, because it's not made of ham. Collins defines misnomer as "an incorrect or unsuitable name or term for a person or thing" and "hamburger" suggest it's a dish once made in Hamburg, so well, it's doesn't suggest any wrong idea. The wrong etymology suggests it, but it's wrong, so we ignore it or else we say that all homophones and words which has homophones inside them are misnomers.

Thanks for this video. I often see people taking language as something that follows very strict rules. The rules changes, so language changes, as they think. Like 3,5" disk can't be called floppy disk, because it wasn't floppy anymore. Or "psychodelik" in Polish is wrong because it's from "psyche", not "psycho". Yeah, it has error, but that's how the things are. If people called the 3,5" disks floppy (classic misnomer), it became floppy. Language isn't about correctness and science/reality is not a proof for how word should sound. The name of my country, Romania, is a misnomer. It comes from Țara Românească – etymologically meaning Land of the Romans. But the problem is that the Romans did not occupy the entirety of the old Dacian kingdom, as the greater part of Moldavia, together with Maramureș and Crișana, was ruled by Free Dacians. The Romans occupied a small part of Dacia from 106 to 274–275 AD. In other words, the Romans occupied less land and for a shorter duration than they did in Britain. A more accurate name for our country would be The United Republic of Transylvania, Wallachia and Moldavia.

Last I heard, french fries is an abbreviation created by two abreviations...

the culinary type of slicing something along it's length in a grid pattern to make rectangles out of it is called the "French Cut" (although I don't know the origin of this) Which means, cutting a cucumber or a pickle in the same way you'd cut a potato to make french fries would make them a "french cut cucumber" and a "french cut pickle"

The term fries actually refers to the method of cooking, being fried, and not baked, boiled, or stewed or souped. So in fact, the term fries developed by abbreviating "fried potatoes"

Together, the original order would be "I would like a side of french cut fried potatoes" which then abbreviated to french fries, keeping the term french as it's original meaning (french cut) but creating a new term from the second abbreviation "fry" or "fries" that applied itself to wedge, curly, Wavy, or any way you choose to dice a potato as long as it's longer than it is high.


Although it's true that french fries were discovered in Belgum, we still use the term french cut today for many culinary dishes.

Addendum to the "French fries" misnomer--For a long period of foundational culinary discovery/evolution in the US, we referred to the Julienne cut as "Frenching".  Carrots, string beans and other long foods in cooking that were cut into uniformly sized "straws" to promote even cooking are all examples of foods commonly "Frenched". Julienne cut potatoes deep fried in oil are "Frenched fried potatoes", which became shortened and colloquialized over the years into "French fries".  This tradition largely continues to this day, as the traditional formal instruction of cooking retains it's heavy French and Italian influences, particularly in the First World.

Making observations and using mathematics to discover how the comet was moving and its orbit around the earth. Edmond Halley was only the curious guy who decided to take a trip to Cambridge to see Isaac Newton. While he was there he wanted Newton to publish his work, but newton didn't carry that kind of money. So Halley published it for him because he was a wealthy merchant. So in reality, Edmond Halley took the credit for one of the greatest astronomical discoveries at the early stages of modern physics.

I doubt that the founding of Singapore was actually based on a lion sighting, whether or not it was actually a lion. Lions were a common highly regarded (mythological) animal in the Indianized Austronesian states in Southeast Asia.

During the 1500s for example, there was a small thalassocratic city-state in the Philippine island of Cebu called Singhapala. Pigafetta, who accompanied Magellan, recorded it as "Cingapola". It means, you guessed it, "Lion City." In Indonesia, as well, you can find numerous depictions of lions in art and folklore. Including the guardian lions of Borobudur and the winged lions of Bali. Lions have never been native to both of these places.

The name was likely simply something that sounded good. In the same way that lions still figured prominently in European heraldry long after they've already been extinct in Europe.

Singaporean here. Virtually all children here learn about the Sang Nila Utama legend that gave Singapore its name in primary school; one version I read about didn't actually describe a lion, but a fantastic beast of some sort (with a multitude of colours) that one of the people accompanying him thought was a lion, but too found it strange that they could be running around here. Regardless, the lion has became a major symbol of our country: our coat of arms has it, we have a national symbol that is a stylised lion's head, one of our two Youth Olympic Games mascots was a lion, and Singapore is often referred to as a Lion City. We even have a Chinese news and current affairs TV show that is literally named "A Date with the Lion City".

Interestingly, I once heard a tale on a local paranormal research website (take it with a grain of salt) that the lion Sang Nila Utama saw might actually be a guardian spirit of Singapore in lion form, contemporaneous with one in the form of a tiger. There's some urban legends that Punggol, a place in the north-eastern part of Singapore, is haunted by the tiger spirit, and once killed several pigs in a pig farm way back when such farms were common here. The paranormal research society did some investigating many, many years back and found a shrine at the now-abolished bus terminus there dedicated to many Chinese deities, including a tiger. Make of this if you will.

I can't believe you didn't bother to mention the months in this video. September is the ninth month of the year, but its prefix, "sept", means seven. October is tenth, but "octo" means eight. Same with the last two months. This is because they were formerly the seventh, eighth, ninth, and tenth month on the old Roman calendar, but the Romans added July and August (named after Julius and Augustus Caesar) to the calendar, therefore nudging these months down by two so now the former seventh month came to be the new ninth month, which is still intact today.

In my language French horn is just 'hoorn’, no mention of what country it comes from. The translation of funny bone is 'telefoonbotje', which mean telephone bone. So yeah, we also call it a bone even though it’s not. My secondary school English teacher told us the 'It’s actually the bell that is called Big Ben' story, so I’m pretty disappointed in him now haha. Never heard of kosher salt. Those oysters that aren’t oysters are called 'Prairie oesters' or 'Rocky Mountain oesters' (oester = oysters), so we make that mistake and we also call those numbers Arabic and those fries French. There’s no nut in my language’s word for peanut, but there is in my language’s word for coconut. The koala bear is called koala or 'buidelbeer’ (which mean pouch bear). But no one says buidelbeer, we all say koala. Eggplant is called 'aubergine' in my language (but that’s also what’s called in English right?). Dry cleaning is called 'chemisch reinigen' which you can translate to 'cleaning chemically’. I’ve always know hamburgers were called after Hamburg. A guinea pigs is called a 'cavia’ so no mention of the word pig in that (but again, cavia also an English word right?). Greenland is called 'Groenland' (groen = green), so that’s also a mistake we make. Parkway is 'parkweg' in my language (way = weg), but 'to park' is translated to 'parkeren’ and 'park' is translated to 'park’, so parkway in my language does make sense. 

Funny how quite a lot of this misnomers are the same in a different language.

Consciousness is you. You cannot experience what others around you experience. You can only experience what happens to you. You think, therefore you are.
When you close yourself in a room devoid of all stimuli and by some means lose every memory and piece of knowledge you've ever gained, you become an existence. You know "you" exists, and nothing more. Time has no meaning, nor would you even be able to comprehend it.
You would no longer be in a universe... You would BE a universe. A universe consisting of your awareness that you exist, and given enough time (whatever "time" is), you might even think of something other than your existence. The moment a single thought formed (from... the mind? Maybe, dare I say... soul?), you would have a seed for other thoughts to grow from. And with each thought, the room devoid of stimuli would start to fill with the materializations of whatever alien concepts your existence came up with. Things would take shape in ways that could only follow whatever laws of physics "you" thought up. But all these things would not be something for you to observe. They would be an extension of your existence. After all... you are a universe. An individual, separate existence shaped only by the stimuli of the world around you.
That, I think, is what consciousness is.

If you haven't already, stop and think about that ending phrase:

"You only live once, but living once means living many times as a series of similar but technically different people who know each other but only in one direction and can help each other but only in the other direction."

Consider your memories.  Consider the things you are happy for and the things you regret doing (or not doing) in life.  Did you perhaps know better at the time?  Did you have enough info at the time to make a better choice, and you chose not to?  Have you chosen each day to avoid doing something you know will make you happier in the long run?

You are painfully aware of the things your past self has done, but under the same token, you are creating history, today, that you will look back on some time in the future.  Your future self will look back on this time with a mixture of emotions, but he/she will either be thankful or disappointed.

Today is the day you can do something right.  You may not want to do it, but someone else will be glad that you did.  That someone else will be you.

'Animalism' is the view that some person is the same person at 'T1' (eg. now) as at 'T2' (eg. in 10 years time) iff (Philosophical jargon for if and only if):
They are the same human animal at T1 and T2. 
So if 'animalism' is correct then Michael is wrong, our personal identity through time is only predicated on our being the same human animal. Since I am the same human animal now as I was 10 years ago I am the same person. 'Animalism' has some pretty intuitive theoretical virtues. It answers questions like "well, aren't I the same person as I was in the womb" with the intuitive answer that yes, I was. 

Michael seems to be employing a 'physically continuous' or 'psychologically continuous' theory of personal identity. This is to say that one is the same person at T1 as at T2 if one is directly (ie. non-transitively) continuous at T2 with either the mental states or physical states at T1. This isn't to say he's not correct, but he doesn't identify this presupposition in the video.

Regarding that last part about skeumorphs: I have a theory that everything new that replaces something before it, keeps parts of that as some kind of common memory, like the snail mail envelop for email for example. There are others:

Before the vacuum cleaner, people used brushes to clean up dirt, and what's on the end of the vacuum cleaner head: a brush.
Before the car and the wheels we all know how they look like (pretty much solid, round blocks of aluminium and rubber) we had horse carts and wagons with spoked wheels. Now, look at some pictures of early cars and their wheels.
It's probably over 20 years ago (if not more - my memory is getting fuzzy) since anyone used a floppy disk the last time to save data on, but its still used as a save icon in many programs.

Now the obvious question is: why? Why do we keep holding on to stuff that makes no sense any longer? Kids of today who have never sent a snail mail don't get the envelope; it's just an odd icon, and they have certainly never made a call on a phone looking like the old kind of phone.

Normally I really like the ideas that get pumped through this channel... but I am extremely tired of this silliness about how much "you now" and "you in the future" are different... it implies such a mind numbingly materialistic and narrow definition of what a person is that it's painful to imagine anyone taking it seriously. A person is a complex, interconnected, (and above all) dynamic pattern in spacetime... not some particular meatsack with any one particular neural snapshot or mindstate. If you're going to take this idea that you in the future is a different person because they don't remember eveything you now is experiencing, then say goodbye to the idea that you now is even really you now, because the vast majority of what is going on inside your head is stuff you aren't consciously aware of... including much of what is needed to be consciously aware. Sure the majority of the lay public has a less than perfect conception of who or what they are, but replacing one skewed notion with another isn't exactly helpful. This is the kind of "it's fun to think about" casual misrepresentation that leads to people believing humans only use 10% of their brain.

If so, and if you haven't already addressed it in another video, I was wondering if you could answer something I'VE been wondering for a while: What would happen if a unit of SPACE was erased/deleted?

It occurred to me one day when I was using the "Cut" function in either a Word document or a Paint program, and I saw how everything to the sides of it just immediately occupied the space. But, if you erased a unit (say, 1 cubic or spherical centimeter) of space, itself, what would happen? Please note that I'm talking about actual SPACE; not matter, not energy, but the actual, physical fabric of reality. Would the entirety of the rest of the universe, down to subatomic level, all simultaneously (and instantaneously, seeing as it wouldn't be a matter of things actually MOVING to fill a suddenly empty space, but rather, that space just not existing anymore... this is REALLY hard for me to put into words) shift into that direction, effectively splitting/compressing every atom in existence? What, if any, effect would there be on time, seeing as space and time are linked (in a way I still don't quite understand)? What about other realities/dimensions (if they have been confirmed to exist; can't quite recall)? Are they tied to our own in any way that such an event would impact them, as well?

I'm deathly curious. It would make for a rather lovely, hilarious doomsday scenario, as well. Rather than blow things up with high-energy beams or explosives, just erase a unit of space the size of the head of a pin and tear the entire universe apart at once.

The future me will still be me, for the single reason that cells, matter, memories get added, or fade, over time. Were someone to change to their future self in an instant, replacing all matter at the exact same time, we might call the result a different person. The reason that I will always be me is that, no matter how much about me changes, I have retained the most fundamental principle of my existance, the thing that makes me me; I am the result of an incredibly complex chain of chemical reactions and events that all started when my mother and father were enjoying themselves a great deal. Even if my mother and father were to die, I would still be the result of that event. Even if I myself were to die, my lifeless body would still be the result of the chain of events, up untill my last bones have degraded into singular atoms.

The other explanation is much more simpel and comes down to the fact that my current conscious considers the old me and the new me to still be me. Language contains an aspect of perspective, and when the future me is still considered to be me from my current perspective, I would logically call it me. The same way I call my cellphone 'my cellphone', despite the fact that it is a completely different object. Reflecting on my original thought, the cellphone has of course also retained it's fundamental principle; it is an object that allows me to communicate over long distance in a certain way, and I consider it to be mine.

The biggest misnomer that I absolutely hate is when people call the US "America." The official name is United States. I know, it's a stupid name, and it's not even a name at all. An adjective with a common noun, some name. What bullshit is that? Canada has its own states (or provinces) that are united, and that is what makes up Canada. Then there is also calling citizens of the US "Americans" when that should really be anyone from the Americas. You'd have to say Pan-American during discussions or people would be confused. Another one is "Asian." Many Russians are indeed Asian, but people keep using Asian to describe orientals. People using race in place of species is annoying too, and when people use words that legitimately do not make sense as a name for races. African American is a dumb term for black "Americans." What if a white guy was from Africa? Sure as hell no one would be calling them an African American, you'd get weird looks. Heck, what if it's really an African Canadian you saw walking down the street? Or maybe, maybe they are just African? But of course, African isn't a race, so it shouldn't be used to describe one. I know words can't always be perfect, but it would be great if the words being used were actually more accurate and followed some sort of logic.
